{"id":"project-LICHEN-3vq3","title":"SLIP transport: IPv6 payload length could cause integer overflow","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/transport/slip_transport.c
Lines: 139-143

In validate_ipv6_packet():

    expected = IPV6_HDR_LEN + ipv6_payload_len(pkt);
    if (expected != len) {
        LOG_WRN("SLIP RX: length mismatch (header says %zu, got %zu)", expected, len);
        return -EINVAL;
    }

ipv6_payload_len() returns uint16_t (line 112):
    return sys_get_be16(&pkt[IPV6_PAYLOAD_OFFSET]);

IPV6_HDR_LEN is 40 (line 104).

If a malicious/corrupted packet has payload_len = 0xFFFF:
- expected = 40 + 65535 = 65575

This exceeds SLIP_LCI_MTU (1280), so the check at line 128-131 should catch it:

    if (len > SLIP_LCI_MTU) {
        LOG_WRN("SLIP RX: packet exceeds MTU (%zu > %u)", len, SLIP_LCI_MTU);
        return -EMSGSIZE;
    }

However, the check is on 'len' (actual received bytes), not 'expected'. A packet could have len=1280 but claim payload_len=65535, which would be rejected by the mismatch check - but the error message would be confusing.

